    <summary>A recent discussion on the bitcoin-dev mailing list brought up concerns about the usability and security of Bitcoin addresses, specifically the Bech32 address format. One issue raised was the lack of visual distinction in the first few bytes of a Bech32 address, making it difficult for users to double-check the address or detect any rogue software that may alter the address.The discussion explored potential solutions, with some users suggesting improving the visual distinctness of the first few bytes in the Bech32 address format. However, no specific solutions were offered. Another issue discussed was the length of Bitcoin addresses, which can cause usability problems in certain contexts.To address this problem, there are suggestions to map a 25-byte address to 16 words from a 6000-word list or to use images based on the bytes of an address using identicon. Despite these suggestions, the actual length of a Bech32 address may not be as problematic as initially thought.Overall, the discussion highlighted the importance of address verification in ensuring the security and accuracy of Bitcoin transactions. Checking only the first few bytes of an address is not sufficient for ensuring its correctness. Ongoing efforts are being made to improve the usability and security of Bitcoin addresses.</summary>
